    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter">
                <head type="title">Camillo Ghilino to Miklós Oláh (Milan, 22 August 1535)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p>He has received Oláh’s letter, from which he has learned about the
                            progress made against the Anabaptists, the outcome of the Lübeck battle,
                            John Fisher’s death, and all the rest. Francesco II Sforza is also
                            sending his regards, with whom they have just heard that the Emperor has
                            conquered Annaba, together with the 15 boats Hayreddin Barbarossa Pasha
                            had left as a watch. A half-naked Barbarossa has fled to Algeria with
                            4,000 soldiers of his; some think that he will perish there and atone
                            for his sins, and this is all the Emperor needs. Oláh will call him a
                            clairvoyant when he sees that Hungary will also belong to the Emperor.
                            He also let the Spanish soldiers go and gathered 4,000 people who had
                            suffered under the Barbarians, to use them against Mauritania, and
                            possibly in Constantinople. There is no news of the Turks, they are busy
                            with the Persians, and the Emperor’s enemies are idle. Ippolito de
                            Medici has been poisoned. </p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p>Idem Nicolao Olao suo salutem. </p>
                <p>Litterae tuae XII. Iulii Idibus Augusti mihi redditae sunt,<note
                        type="critic">We do not know this letter.</note> ex his, quae in Germania
                    adversus anabaptistas egregie facta sunt, percepi. Item exitum pugnae
                    Lubeccensium in <persName>ducem</persName><note type="critic">King Christian III
                        of Denmark.</note> Olsaciae, <persName>Ruffensis</persName><note
                        type="critic">John Fisher.</note> occasum,<note type="critic">John Fisher
                        was executed on 22 June, 1535 at the order of King Henry VIII. For more his
                        execution, see <hi rend="smallcap">De Vocht</hi> 1961, 249–252.</note> et
                    quicquid apud vos novi erat. <persName>Princeps</persName><note type="critic"
                        >Francesco II Sforza.</note> meus, quoniam tuo nomine salutavi, de his
                    omnibus seorsum tibi gratias agit et te resalutat. Nunc primum accepimus
                        <persName>caesaris</persName> classem <placeName>Bonam</placeName>,<note
                        type="critic">Annaba.</note> urbem Bartanae maritinam intercepisse cum XV
                    triremibus <persName>Aenobarbi</persName>,<note type="critic">Hayreddin
                        Barbarossa Pasha.</note> quas eo loci ad tuenda omnia illa habebat; urbs a
                    militibus direpta, triremes incensae. <persName>Aenobarbus</persName> cum CCCC
                    Turcis militibus seminudus vix aufugit Algerium versus. Sunt, qui putent hominem
                    minime Arabum manus evasurum, in ipsoque itinere praeteritorum peccatorum poenas
                    daturum, hoc tantum ad solidam Dei nostri caesaris felicitatem deerat. Quid quod
                    et Hungaria ipsa ad eius imperium accedat, quo tempore me verissimum vatem
                    profiteberis et in secundis rebus tuis mei aliquando mentionem facies. Caesar
                    dimissis Hispanis militibus ad quatuor millia hominum conduxit ex his, qui
                    diuturnam servitutem apud barbaros inserviverunt, horum opera ad debellandam
                        <placeName>Mauritimam</placeName><note type="critic">I.e. Mauritania.</note>
                    omnem utetur, et fortassis in <placeName>Constantinopolitana</placeName>
                    expeditione. De Turca nihil novi habemus, ei instabat <persName>Persarum
                        rex</persName>.<note type="critic">Tahmasp I, Shah of Iran.</note> Caesaris
                    hostes, quos hoc tempore videtis, toti frigent. <del corresp="Olahus"
                        >Marises</del><persName><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr">Medices</add>
                        cardinalis</persName><note type="critic">Ippolito de’ Medici suffered from
                        fever before he died. He probably died from malaria and was not poisoned,
                        although there were such rumours, see <hi rend="smallcap">Crews</hi> 2003,
                        109. For background, see Ep. 540.</note><ref>/o:olahus.tei.15350630_1</ref>
                    veneno necatus est. Vale et frequenter scribe, et
                        <persName>Sceppero</persName><note type="critic">Cornelis de
                        Schepper.</note> et reliquis amicis me commenda.
                        <persName>Gemmae</persName><note type="critic">Jemme Reinerszoon.</note>
                    libellos accepi et de his tibi gratias habeo, miror ensem adhuc esse in itinere.
                    Iterum vale. </p>
                <p><placeName>Mediolano</placeName> X. Kalendas Septembris, hoc est XXII.
                    Augusti 1535.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
